## Workaround

This can be solved externally in the meantime using a special component:

```jsx
const scrollerStyles: React.CSSProperties = {
  width: '100%',
  height: '100%',
  overflowY: 'auto',
  overscrollBehavior: 'none',
  scrollbarWidth: 'none',
  // For old Safari, a class with `::-webkit-scrollbar{display:none}` is needed
};

const overflowWrapperStyles: React.CSSProperties = {
  height: 'calc(100% + 1px)',
};

const stickyWrapperStyles: React.CSSProperties = {
  position: 'sticky' as const,
  top: 0,
  bottom: 0,
  height: 'calc(100% - 1px)',
};

function ScrollLock({ children }) {
  return (
    <div style={scrollerStyles}>
      <div style={overflowWrapperStyles}>
        <div style={stickyWrapperStyles}>{children}</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Usage

`<Dialog.Viewport>` was released after `beta.4`, but you can use a `<div>`:

```jsx
<Dialog.Portal>
  <Dialog.Viewport
    render={(props, state) => (
      <div
        {...props}
        style={{
          position: 'fixed',
          inset: 0,
          // Just so long exit animations don't block scroll
          pointerEvents: state.open ? 'auto' : 'none',
          ...props.style,
        }}
      />
    )}
  >
    <ScrollLock>
      <Dialog.Popup />
    </ScrollLock>
  </Dialog.Viewport>
</Dialog.Portal>
```

Thanks very much for this. It's crazy the hacks we've had to go through to make a usable dialog box on iOS, thanks Safari!. Hoping Base UI merge this or a similar fix soon.

Just for anyone copy-pasting using Tailwind/Typescript, here's the `ScrollLock` component @atomiks wrote with Tailwind and accepting a className. We have an opinionated wrapper around Dialog.Viewport which passes className down to this rather than puts it on Viewport so we can still add the flex styling etc.

```tsx
function ScrollLock({ children, className }: PropsWithChildren<{ className?: string }>) {
  return (
    <div className="scrollbar-none size-full overflow-y-auto overscroll-none">
      <div className="h-[calc(100%+1px)]">
        <div className={twMerge('sticky top-0 bottom-0 flex h-[calc(100%-1px)]', className)}>
          {children}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  )
}
```

tailwind `theme.css`:
```css
@utility scrollbar-none {
  -ms-overflow-style: none;
  scrollbar-width: none;

  &::-webkit-scrollbar {
    display: none;
  }
}
```

@rikbrown unfortunately this is a tricky problem to address on the library's side. iOS is a _huge_ pain in this regard.

While the wrapper elements seem to work robustly, we can't add this as part of the library because it breaks the "component-per-node" layout expectations (e.g. `display: flex` doesn't work as expected). The only realistic solution is to add it to the docs demo (manually), but that looks pretty messy.

There are libraries that handle this in a more general way (without needing wrappers), but they're very prone to breaking other behaviors on iOS (see dot points for instance, but there are various others) and add a bunch of extra code (CPU + bundle cost) which is why we accepted the scroll lock not working fully on iOS at this point in time

> what you are suggesting sounds a bit like stepping into z index hell

100%, that's annoying. A better workaround is removing the pointer-events from the internal backdrop when rendering your own. Of course this is just a workaround, not a permanent fix - Base UI shouldn't interfere with your styles here to begin with.

```js
<Dialog.Backdrop
  ref={React.useCallback((node) => {
    const internalBackdrop = node && node.nextElementSibling;
    if (internalBackdrop?.role === 'presentation') {
      internalBackdrop.style.pointerEvents = "none";
    }
  }, [])}
/>
```

The `cursor: pointer` thing is more of a personal gripe I have with web apps overusing the style, but in the case of a backdrop, it seems particularly unnecessary (compared to say buttons). For instance, Instagram and GitHub both don't set it on their modal dialogs. Why do you think users need to see the cursor change when hovering the backdrop if the biggest websites, nor OS modals, don't change it? Backdrops are already assumed to be clickable to dismiss, since it's a common UI paradigm

You can use a generic, then it can for example infer the type of the value in `onValueChange`:
